				<div id="bodyContent" class="vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleTarget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby="firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-container="">
					<div class="vector-body-before-content">
							<div class="mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id="contentSub"><div id="mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
					
					
					<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><p class="mw-empty-elt">

</p>
<figure class="mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Nintendo_3DS_case_banners.png" class="mw-file-description"><img src="List%20of%20Nintendo%203DS%20games%20-%20Wikipedia_files/Nintendo_3DS_case_banners_002.png" decoding="async" width="300" height="160" class="mw-file-element" srcset="List%20of%20Nintendo%203DS%20games%20-%20Wikipedia_files/Nintendo_3DS_case_banners.png 1.5x" data-file-width="410" data-file-height="219"></a><figcaption>The
 international white Nintendo 3DS banner used on current and upcoming 
retail game covers (top). In Japan, the banner is black for Nintendo 3DS
 games rated by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_Entertainment_Rating_Organization" title="Computer Entertainment Rating Organization">CERO</a> as C or D (bottom). <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Nintendo_Network_games#Nintendo_3DS" class="mw-redirect" title="List of Nintendo Network games">Nintendo Network-compatible games</a> feature a small logo on top of the banner, but as of November 2014, the small <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amiibo" title="Amiibo">Amiibo</a>
 logo is dominantly featured instead, even if said games also supported 
Nintendo Network. The Nintendo Network logo will continue to feature if 
Amiibo support is definitely absent. On actual retail game case covers, 
the banner is flipped vertically. Game cases for games dedicated 
exclusively to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Nintendo_3DS" title="New Nintendo 3DS">New Nintendo 3DS</a> (such as <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xenoblade_Chronicles_3D" class="mw-redirect" title="Xenoblade Chronicles 3D">Xenoblade Chronicles 3D</a></i>) feature a different template layout.</figcaption></figure>
<p>This is a list of all video games released for the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nintendo_3DS" title="Nintendo 3DS">Nintendo 3DS</a>. For games that were announced or in-development, but never released, see the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cancelled_Nintendo_3DS_games" title="List of cancelled Nintendo 3DS games">list of cancelled Nintendo 3DS games</a>.
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Games">Games</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_Nintendo_3DS_games&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Games"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Nintendo 3DS portable system has a large library of games, which are released in game card and/or digital form.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This list does not include downloadable games available via the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_Console" title="Virtual Console">Virtual Console</a> service.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nintendo_3DS_family" class="mw-redirect" title="Nintendo 3DS family">Nintendo 3DS family</a> is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backward_compatible" class="mw-redirect" title="Backward compatible">backward compatible</a> with its predecessor, the Nintendo DS line, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Nintendo_DS_games" class="mw-redirect" title="List of Nintendo DS games">its software</a>, including most <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_DSiWare_games_and_applications" class="mw-redirect" title="List of DSiWare games and applications">DSi software</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
The list is initially organized alphabetically by their English titles 
or their alphabet conversions, but it is also possible to sort each 
column individually by clicking the square icon at the top of each 
column. The Nintendo 3DS system is region locked, meaning that in 
reality each system has a restricted library of games to select from, 
depending on the region of the device;<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the list below displays the availability of games within each of the four regions.
</p><p>For a chronological list, click the sort button in any of the 
available regions' column. Games dated February 26, 2011, (Japan), March
 25, 2011, (Europe), March 27, 2011, (North America), and March 31, 
2011, (Australia) are the launch titles of each respective region.
</p><p>There are <b>1807</b><sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> games on this list.
</p>

<tr>
<td id="0–9"><i>10-in-1: Arcade Collection</i>
</td>
<td>Gamelion Studios
</td>
<td>Gamelion Studios
</td>
<td><span data-sort-value="000000002014-03-26-0000" style="white-space:nowrap">March 26, 2014</span></td>
